",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class dependencies**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I should pin the old jar dependency version. Testing the current library gives no clear answer. I wonder if existing class bytes transformation can help remove a method, but dynamic class loading isn’t supported, which complicates things. Should I consider subclassing LoggingEvent? The method I’m looking at isn’t final, so I can override it, but there’s so much to cover in terms of testing. I think minimizing and justifying reflection uses could be necessary. Using Method directly might be okay here?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating reflection and metadata**\\n\\nI'm trying to sort out the nuances of using reflection. The phrase \\\"public API requires naturally\\\" isn't entirely straightforward. If I'm accessing a private field or constructor via reflection, I need the reachability metadata generated by an agent. That seems acceptable, especially since tests run with a Java agent can generate this metadata. However, for native image tests, if no metadata is checked in, I'm wondering if it's still allowed when Forge merges externally. They do mention not modifying metadata, so I need to tread carefully here.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_KUvPLZ8rvXs8VBMdRAbWOQvA|fc_0cf590b1158c60b70169fb9f7f5ae48191ab75c02999ead127", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nprint(len('org.apache.log4j.spi.LoggingEvent'))\nprint(len('org.apache.log4j.pattern.LogEvent'))\nPY"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1244, "output": 834, "cacheRead": 16896, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 18974, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778098032934, "responseId": "resp_0cf590b1158c60b70169fb9f71a88881918a31b50d7bc395ba"}}
